Mortality in Europe

library("lubridate")
library("here")
library("tidyverse")
library("janitor")

theme_set(theme_minimal())

Data source: https://www.mortality.org.

Step 1: read the data (England & Wales first)

If you inspect the data, youll see that we have a whitespace-delimited file where each line is the same length, and each field is in the same position in every line. This is a job for the readr function read_table(). Two other issues to deal with:

  • The first two columns of the text file should be skipped
  • Missing values are coded as .
england <- here("12_data-manip2.5", "England_Mx_1x1.txt") %>% 
  read_table(skip = 2, na = ".")

knitr::kable(head(england))
Year Age Female Male Total
1841 0 0.136067 0.169189 0.152777
1841 1 0.059577 0.063208 0.061386
1841 2 0.036406 0.036976 0.036689
1841 3 0.024913 0.026055 0.025480
1841 4 0.018457 0.019089 0.018772
1841 5 0.013967 0.014279 0.014123

Some issues:

  • We need the country name in there.
  • The age column is stored as text because people older than 110 are coded as 110+, which isnt a valid number.

There are a variety of ways to deal with the last problem, but maybe the easiest is to use the readr function parse_number(), which extracts the numeric part of a mixed text/number string.

Step 2: clean the names/text

england <- england %>%
  clean_names() %>% 
  mutate(country = "England & Wales",
         age = parse_number(age))

knitr::kable(head(england))

Step 3: do the same for France

france <- here("12_data-manip2.5", "France_Mx_1x1.txt") %>% 
  read_table(skip = 2, na = ".") %>%
  clean_names() %>%
  mutate(country = "France",
         age = parse_number(age))

Step 4: combine the data

Two data frames with the same columns can be bound together row-wise using the dplyr function bind_rows().

deaths <- bind_rows(england, france)

Step 5: pivot to longer format

Eventually, we need to facet by both country and sex. However, we currently have male and female mortality rates in different columns. To facet correctly, well need to reshape to a tidy format with one column that indicates sex and another column that indicates the death rate.

deaths <- deaths %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(male, female), names_to = "sex", values_to = "death_rate")

knitr::kable(head(deaths))
year age total country sex death_rate
1841 0 0.152777 England & Wales male 0.169189
1841 0 0.152777 England & Wales female 0.136067
1841 1 0.061386 England & Wales male 0.063208
1841 1 0.061386 England & Wales female 0.059577
1841 2 0.036689 England & Wales male 0.036976
1841 2 0.036689 England & Wales female 0.036406

Step 6: Calculate percentiles (and relabel sexes)

Lets relabel the sexes as Women and Men using the forcats function fct_recode(). Finally, we can make a new column with percentile bins using the dplyr function ntile(). This will be mapped to fill in our tile plot.

deaths <- deaths %>% 
  mutate(sex = fct_recode(sex, "Women" = "female", "Men" = "male"),
         death_ntile = ntile(death_rate, 100))

knitr::kable(head(deaths))
year age total country sex death_rate death_ntile
1841 0 0.152777 England & Wales Men 0.169189 78
1841 0 0.152777 England & Wales Women 0.136067 76
1841 1 0.061386 England & Wales Men 0.063208 68
1841 1 0.061386 England & Wales Women 0.059577 67
1841 2 0.036689 England & Wales Men 0.036976 62
1841 2 0.036689 England & Wales Women 0.036406 62

Step 7: tile plot

ggplot(filter(deaths, age < 101), aes(x = year, y = age, fill = death_ntile)) +
  geom_raster() +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "magma", breaks = seq(10, 100, by = 10)) +
  facet_grid(country ~ sex) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1820, 2015, by = 25)) +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(nrow = 1, title.position = "top",
                             label.position = "bottom")) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 100)) +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Age", fill = "Death Rate Percentile",
       title = "Mortality Rates in Western Europe, 1816-2016",
       subtitle = "Binned by percentile",
       caption = "Data from The Human Mortality Database (https://www.mortality.org/)") +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom",
        legend.justification = c("left", "center"),
        legend.key.width = unit(1, "cm"))
